    {
      "id": "66665c5c804cda58eb7eeb46f881b8d55c901618",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 284,
        "name": "Emoly Liu",
        "email": "emoly@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "liuying_emoly"
      },
      "date": "2013-08-08 05:54:16.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nThis is a client side patch, which is a direct port of  Linus' commit 73bb1da692d0dc3e93b9c9e29084d6a5dcbc37a6. It has no \"HAVE_ONLY_PROCFS_SEQ\"  defined in http://review.whamcloud.com/#/c/7135 .\n\nNow it's just a fortestonly patch because I'm not sure if it can't pass Hudson build and can be landed without server side patch. It works well on my local VM(rhel6), and I want to know if it works as well on 3.10 kernel.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "b6ed1ca5f2f4b638122cfd10465cc9aebf57e99d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 2,
        "name": "Jenkins",
        "username": "hudson",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-08-08 06:49:26.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nBuild Started http://build.whamcloud.com/job/lustre-reviews/17279/ ",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "1431e3afcfb6b7feb974f53b7788f1d701278b12",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 2,
        "name": "Jenkins",
        "username": "hudson",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-08-08 07:13:17.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: Fails\n\nBuild Failed \n \nhttp://build.whamcloud.com/job/lustre-reviews/17279/ : FAILURE",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "4717741ad5181bca2155fbde6926da06fd2d8992",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 284,
        "name": "Emoly Liu",
        "email": "emoly@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "liuying_emoly"
      },
      "date": "2013-08-08 07:21:03.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nBob, this patch is to adapt lustre client code to 3.10 upstream kernel proc_dir_entry change. As I said in my previous comment, it is a direct port of Linus'(PengTao's) commit 73bb1da692d0dc3e93b9c9e29084d6a5dcbc37a6. It has no \"HAVE_ONLY_PROCFS_SEQ\".\n\nCould you please do me a help to test it on your 3.10 kernel and see if it works? Thanks.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "04c210f5ba3ba32df8455edf324c7dc29b9e314b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 251,
        "name": "Bob Glossman",
        "email": "bob.glossman@intel.com",
        "username": "bogl",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-08-08 15:19:33.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nEmoly,  I can't get this patch to apply cleanly onto the current master.  It comes closest to going in if I don't try to apply James' set of patches first; #7135, #7139, #7140.  Is this patch intended to be instead of those, or in addition to those?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "b2f0bdb8005aa3d693837cf3f28839df6dbe7fb9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 284,
        "name": "Emoly Liu",
        "email": "emoly@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "liuying_emoly"
      },
      "date": "2013-08-09 01:37:46.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nBob, this patch is intended to be instead of those, but now it is client only. Since proc_subdir_lock is not exported in all kernels, we have to keep lproc_lock and lprocfs_srch() in server side.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "a233caf315b611c216a74251b821b8a1a0e9cbd8",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 251,
        "name": "Bob Glossman",
        "email": "bob.glossman@intel.com",
        "username": "bogl",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-08-09 01:58:52.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nEmoly, If that is the case then I can't get this patch to apply.  If I manually tweak it so it goes in (more or less) I can't build, even client only.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "a6b12c10b21dd06598868db4ff897e459b85dfab",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 284,
        "name": "Emoly Liu",
        "email": "emoly@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "liuying_emoly"
      },
      "date": "2013-08-09 03:13:32.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nThanks! Let me rebase and update it.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "365e790682b250cff9b03d186c859f19161ab294",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-12-16 19:36:35.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nI think this patch can be abandoned, since James Simmons has submitted separate patches to fix lprocfs and most of them are landed.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "45c3470fd1aa83775e104a268ef852418e54b94d",
      "author": {
